{{About|the hill and refuge castle in the Lippe Uplands|the hillfort on the Süntel|Amelungsburg (Süntel)}} {{Infobox mountain |name= Amelungsburg |photo=Amelungsburg.jpg |photo_caption=Amelungsburg in the Lippe Uplands |photo_size= |elevation_m=292 |elevation_ref = |prominence_m = |prominence_ref= |location=[[North Rhine-Westphalia]], [[Germany]] |range=[[Lippe Uplands]] |map = Germany North Rhine-Westphalia#Germany |map_size = 220 |coordinates = {{coord|52.04778|N|8.98417|E|type:mountain_region:DE-NW_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} |coords_ref = |range_coordinates = |type=[[Keuper]] |age= |first_ascent= |easiest_route= }} The '''Amelungsburg''' is a {{convert|292|m|ft|0|adj=on}} high hill in the [[Lippe Uplands]] in central Germany, in the municipality of [[Dörentrup]] in the district of [[Kreis Lippe|Lippe]].
The Amelungsburg is believed to be the observation hill (''Warthberg'') belonging to the [[Piepenkopf]] rampart system located on its south-southwestern spur.<ref>Friedrich Hohenschwert: "Ur- und Frühgeschichtliche Befestigungen in Lippe". Herausgegeben von der Altertumskommission für Westfalen, Münster, 1978</ref> Investigations into the charred remains (''Brandfunde'') at the site of the settlement with its double-embankment have been dated to 250 B.C. and can thus be presumed to have belonged to the [[La Tène culture]]. The settlement was not rebuilt. [[File:Amelungsburg_Plan.jpg|thumb|left|1878 plan of the Amelungsburg]] At the southwestern foot of the Amelungsburg today is a still easily recognised, roughly 2-metre-high section of the [[rampart (fortification)|ramparts]] with a 1.5-metre-deep [[ditch (fortification)|ditch]]. It is suspected that this advanced rampart used to guard the road system.<ref name="Vor- und frühgeschichtliche Burgen in Lippe">{{citation/core|Surname1=Leo Nebelsiek|Title=Vor- und frühgeschichtliche Burgen in Lippe, Lippischer Kalender |Year=1950|Date= 1950|language=German}}</ref>
In order to beat looters, the refuge castle has been investigated. Excavations on the plateau of the Amelungsburg unearthed about 300 individual items. In a number of spots there were both single and multiple hordes of goods. {{clear left}} == References == {{Reflist}}
