'''Peter John Murray''' (London, 1920 – 1992, [[Farnborough, Warwickshire]])<ref name=dict>[http://www.dictionaryofarthistorians.org/murrayp.htm Murray, Peter [John<nowiki>]</nowiki>.] Dictionary of Art Historians, 2013. Retrieved 30 January 2013. [https://www.webcitation.org/6E3gi9NWA Archived here.]</ref> was a Professor of History of Art at [[Birkbeck College]], London, from 1967,<ref>[http://www.bbk.ac.uk/art-history/about-us/murray-trust Murray Bequest.] Birkbeck College, 27 March 2012. Retrieved 31 January 2013. [https://www.webcitation.org/6E4Syc7Vw Archived here.]</ref> succeeding [[Nikolaus Pevsner]]. He retired in 1980 and was succeeded in turn by [[John Steer (art historian)|John Steer]].<ref name=dict/>

Together with his wife '''Linda Murray''' (née Bramley, 1913–2004),<ref name="Draper">{{cite news|last=Draper|first=Peter|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/nov/24/guardianobituaries.obituaries1|title=Linda Murray|work=The Guardian|date=24 November 2004|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref> Peter Murray wrote primers about Italian [[Renaissance art]] which have been used by generations of students. Linda Murray also wrote several books on her own, and completed their collaboration ''The Oxford Companion To Christian Art And Architecture'' (1996) after her husband died.<ref name="Draper"/>

